text: My theory as of now:  If "Get Out" was about white supremacy and the exploitation of Black bodies, "Us" is a metaphor for Black Americans overcompensating and/or trying to assimilate into white America. (i.e. the mom trying to get her son on rhythm, the father getting the boat, etc). Then after seeing all the rabbits â€” a symbol for procreation/family/lineage/fertilityâ€” I think there's a metaphor somewhere about this new generation of middle-class suburban Black families still trying to hold onto Black urban culture when they're far removed from it (i.e. The parents playing "I got 5 on it" while driving to a vacation house with their white friends at the beach). Hmm, maybe the whole movie is about code-switching â€” the people we present ourselves as and the people we really are. Idk. Excited to see it though and really just wrote this out to distract me from how creepy this was.

text: Theory: What if the plot is not about you being your worse enemy but it's a parallel universe where being good and pure is the norm vs. a society where evil and temptations are widely except. Take for instance how the characters are portrayed, the normal/good family are viewed in a light. You can see it in how they are dress, bright and light colors, and almost every frame where they don't encounter their doppelgangers, it is bright/good. While in this parallel universe they dress in red which could represent evil/temptations. Their norm is doing whatever deep dark desire they have, for example the doppelganger boy has a fixation on fire. There's like 3 shots were he's seen with fire, the one where he was walking through the fire, when he was in the closet with the other boy, he was holding a lighter I think, and the third shot where they showed a close up on his face and it was burned. That could represent his evil desire. The doppelgangers could be seeing the normal family as threats to their norms and understanding of the world and that's why they're hunting them or the complete opposite. The doppelgangers might be there to show the good family that it's ok to embrace their dark/evil tendencies. There's 2 parts of the trailer that can support this: 1. Where the evil mom doppelganger tells the good family to 'be careful'. Why would she warn them if they were against them? And the part where the two boys were in the closet playing with the fire and looking at each other. The doppelganger didn't look threatening but as if he was showing the good boy their possibly shared fascination with fire. The doppelgangers seem to be somehow connected with the scissors. There was that scene where they were holdings each other's scissors which could symbolize being unified/separate idk. Wow that was long, but what do y'all think?

Its a Black-American Family.... more BLACK... than actually AMERICAN... maybe considered TOO BLACK by some.... And a result of Isolated Toxic Tribalism in the Black Community/Black Family structure/unit.... Think of it...  It all started with a old-school "RAP" song about "Drugs" that was just suppose to be a cool song and was harmlessly & inadvertently trying to come across as "cool/hip/innocent" to young black children of THIS Generation who have no idea what that "LIFE" was about... But Black folks 35+ know and we consciously struggle with "THAT LIFE" and the temptation it brings with listening to the lyrics of old school hip hop songs that remind us of where we come from and how far we've come in spite of whatever modern injustices occurring in the Black Communities.... My kids are here listening to it...ğŸ˜¬"... text: I'm realizing something after having a conversation with my cousin. She was saying White directors just don't know what to do with us in horror films. So they just kill us off because we get too loud and make too much sense of the insidious horror. They don't even know how we will react in such situations in horror films. This makes sense for a lot of Hollywood with these horror films. White directors think the way they do because it's their reality. This is why I'm thankful for Jordan Peele because not only is he black but he is casting black characters and we are getting great horror/thrillers that are not cheesy in any way. We need more black directors serious and passionate about horror that can actually cast black people. Maybe this is why some black people don't like scary movies because they don't find them realistic and don't find the characters relatable but Jordan has been doing something.

text: The Tethered are the monsters in this movie, they found a way to come to our side of the world and are trying to take over...Lupitia as a child came across them before, hence her knowing about them, look in the background of several scenes, there's bodies everywhere, that's because it's not just happening to them, it's happening to the whole town...The Tethered are killing the "real" version and Lupitia and her family are trying to find out how to stop them...this film isn't about race, but it is the first time an African American family has been featured as leads in a movie like this...it's kinda like Invasion of the Body Snatchers...it's always been a white person or their family...so Jordan Peele wanted to make a horror film where we got to see from our POV what we would do and how we would handle ourselves in this situation... we're not looking at "them" in this situation, we're looking at "us" in this situation

The Protagonist/ MC of this Japanese comic is a teenage boy whose friend died in accident many years ago, many believe she is died by accident from drowing in the sea.  However after years, he met his friend again, but this time there are two person with exactly the same body and face that looks similiar to his friend.  Turn out One is the real one, however the other one is the fake. They realized that the fake one is the one behind the drowning accident years ago and it is trying to kill his friend as it trying to replace the real one. However even after years missing the girl miraculously alive out of time. The MC then figured out that something terrible about these creature. It not just one but many. Turns out many human populace in that island also has been killed and have been replaced by these creature whose able to copycat their body exactly like their victim.  Even the protagonist started to being targeted by his body double.   This body double, whatever they're called also desrcibed exactly like this movie version explained. They're us, they think like us, they know where we we are, and they're  not going to stop until they kill us. text: I just saw an ad for this movie on a video I was about to watch. The ad was a skipable ad, but the first few seconds reeled me in so I decided to watch the whole thing and boy let me tell you I should have skipped it! I should have skipped it, because by the end of that trailer THE WHOLE ENTIRE MOVIE WAS GIVEN AWAY! Why the hell do trailers do that nowadays? I mean why am I going to go pay $10 for the movie ticket and another $10 on snacks when I ALREADY KNOW THE MOVIE'S PLOT POINTS FROM THE DANG TRAILER?? Is it so hard nowadays to leave the title and movie premise connection out of the trailer? I did NOT need to know from the trailer why the movie is called US. That is the fun of going to a movie! You see some things you like in the trailer, as it draws you in, making you think "Why is this movie called US?" or "Who are those people following them?" or "Why are those people following them?". Now I may not know the reason for the people following them, BUT I SURE AS HELL KNOW WHO THE PEOPLE ARE and WHY THE MOVIE IS CALLED US! Thank you for saving me $20+ going to see this movie, because now I can just sit my ass at home and wait for it for FREE on my firestick.
